Title: Tender is the Flesh
Author: Agustina Bazterrica
My Review:
You may ask yourself what the fuck did I just read? I had to force myself to take breaks.. don’t let the short page count fool you, you probably won’t be able to read this but for 20 minutes at a time

Personally i love an unreliable narrator, I was definitely skeptical. 4/5. The book you wish you could put down and you’re weary of answering “oh what are you reading?”.

At times disgusting, unbelievable, or even “how could someone type the words on this actual page?”, moments..

Be weary of trigger warnings before reading- abuse, animal abuse, SA, and graphic descriptions of dystopian society that seem so far gone, it’s insane.

Around pages 148-153.. I think could have been left out. I was warned by a friend to skip over it.

I should have listened.

You’ll read along, ask yourself what’s the point, and then have an “aha!” moment that the author literally saves for the last paragraph.

Title: Where the Crawdads Sing
Author: Delia Owens
My Review:
SPOILERS AHEAD, but here we goooo

First off i wish to preface this with- I’ve had this novel for a while now and not sure why i never had the urge to pick it up. Once hearing about the movie, i told myself that I would read it before the movie released. I woke up today realizing that was today- and started it this morning. I finished it tonight. These are some thoughts that i communicated to my best friends immediately after giving 5 stars to this book that i just assumed (incorrectly) that i would dislike. I HAVE NOT SEEN THE FILM YET- again SPOILERS AHEAD for the NOVEL.

I loved that Tate was the only one who knew.
I love that she had a motive but wouldn’t have been respected if she claimed self defense because she was the “marsh girl” I love how it highlighted isolation and finding peace in small things.
I love how the author explained loneliness that you nearly rely on EVERY TINY interaction to get by. That even a small conversation is okay for a few days- but if she didn’t have the interaction, she backslid. It reminded me of how much everyone needs someone.
No matter how many people left her, only one came back. She had her guard up- but it was struck down by being honest with only one person- the only person she ever loved. She was strong to defend herself against Chase, and weak for not being able to participate in the privileged society- but that did not matter, Tate saw her for her potential- and even though he could have been exiled from the community for being so close to her, he was the only one- the only one- who believed she could be more than what everyone else said she was.
even when she didn’t believe it herself.

Anyways, that was more of a brain dump than a formal review but- hey- for what it’s worth I’m elated that I read this novel, and I understand the hype now.

Title: Magpie
Author: Elizabeth Day
My Review:
Tbh this book could have gone in so many directions. The plot set up was immaculate in my opinion- unfortunately the story fell flat. This incredible build up for what could have been a pregnancy thriller- all comes down to little to no resolve.

I went in with high expectations given the summary and reviews, but I feel I am the minority here with not really understanding the overall meaning- set up for betrayal, murder, thriller vibes- it leaves you with a “Leave it to Beaver” style epilogue.

Title: Choke
Author: Chuck Palahniuk
My Review:
For me thus book was well out of my comfort zone, genre wise. While very well written, the opening line of the book is correct. You don’t really WANT to read this book, but once you start you somehow have to finish- even if it’s not something you’re not enjoying.

I found myself- although encapsulated by the unfamiliar grit- wincing at so many of uniquely stylized scenes that Chuck creates throughout the short chapters. The only reason to keep reading is to figure out what the hell he’s going to say next- which is all it took for me to finish it in 3 days.

Title: Eleanor Oliphant Is Completely Fine
Author: Gail Honeyman
My Review:
NO SPOILERS:
“Eleanor Oliphant is Completely Fine” feels like such a needed hug. For anyone who has been through, really, .. anything- this book is for you. Hope courage, and heartwarming chapters. The heroine is so unlikely- she is like no other character I’ve read before. Honeyman’s realistic view of the world through Eleanor’s eyes is charming.

Beautifully paced writing , and meaningful dialogue brings you to a surprising twist- but oddly enough- it is a grain of salt when compared to the true meaning of Eleanor’s story- hope and recovery.

All awhile she’s looking for a way out, she makes it out in an unlikely way with the help of an unlikely friend. Gladly, and for a nice change- it is not a love story- but one of companionship and healing.

Witty, charming, and delightful- Eleanor will stay with me forever.
